t_t&`, take the negation and annotate directly, or restructure so the recursive call receives the corrected commodity without an extra heap allocation:\n\n```cpp\nif (!amt.commodity().has_annotation() && amt.sign() < 0) {\n  const string& base_symbol = amt.commodity().base_symbol();\n  for (amounts_map::value_type& pair : amounts) {\n    if (pair.first->has_annotation() && pair.first->base_symbol() == base_symbol) {\n      // Subtract directly from the existing lot entry to avoid re-entering\n      // operator-= and the second map scan:\n      pair.second -= amt.abs();   // amt.abs() is still O(1) on the quantity\n      pair.second.set_commodity(*pair.first);  // commodity already correct\n      if (pair.second.is_realzero())\n        amounts.erase(amounts_map::iterator(&pair));\n      return *this;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### [MEDIUM] Recursive `operator-=` re-scans the entire `amounts` map a second time\n\n- **File**: `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/fix-164/src/balance.cc#L102-L113`\n- **Category**: Performance\n- **Confidence**: 92\n- **Problem**: When the new branch at line 105 finds a matching lot, it constructs `annotated_amt` and calls `*this -= annotated_amt` recursively. The recursive call re-enters `operator-=` from the top, which immediately calls `find_by_name` (a full linear scan of `amounts` at lines 93-94), performing a second O(n) walk over the same map that was just walked to find the lot at line 105. With a balance containing `n` lots of the same base commodity, each unannotated sale thus costs O(n) to find the lot plus O(n) to re-find it via the recursive call — O(2n) per subtraction instead of O(n).\n- **Impact**: For accounts holding many lots of the same commodity (common in investment journals), each lot-matched sale triggers two full scans of the amounts map. If the balance has 50 lots of AAPL, that is 100 map iterations per subtraction instead of 50. This doubles the cost of the most common lot-matching operation.\n- **Fix**: After finding th